r and inextricably bound up with anthropological fieldwork. The volume is put together accordingly: Precisely by mixing ostensibly philosophical papers with papers that engage in close anthropological study of concrete issues, it is meant to reflect the vital tie between these two aspects of the overall philosophical-anthropological enterprise. The collection will be of great interest to philosophers and anthropologists alike, and essential reading for anyone interested in the interconnections between the two disciplines.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aPhilosophical anthropology. 4aExperimentalpsychologie. 4aIndividuum. 4aMenschliche Natur. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh1 aBevir, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahill, Kevin M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCahill, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDescombes, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGustafsson, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGustafsson, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIngold, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLock, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShildrick, Margrit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSvendsen, Lars Fr. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWentzer, Thomas Schwarz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWentzer, Thomas Schwarz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of